All 72 counties of Wisconsin are represented. Islands in Lake Michigan and Lake Superior belonging to Wisconsin counties are also represented.

prcStep.stepDesc: Two polygons to the west of the Apostle Islands in Lake Superior (coded as being part of Bayfield County) were found to be shoals rather than islands. The polygons were part of the 24K Hydrography database used as the original source for most of the Great Lakes shoreline in Wisconsin, and were erroneously included in the 24K County Boundaries data. DNR staff removed the polygons from the Wisconsin County Boundaries polygon (region) feature class in November, 2010.

stepProc.rpOrgName: Wisconsin DNR, Bureau of Technology Services

prcStep.stepDesc: Linework from the Wisconsin 24K State Boundaries data layer was used for portions of county boundaries that form the periphery of the state. Linework from the 1:24,000-scale Landnet layer were used for portions of county boundaries that coincide with PLSS lines. Portions of county boundaries in surface water features in the interior of the state were digitized on-screen using 1:24,000-scale digital raster graphics. Linework from the 1:24,000-scale Hydrography layer were used for the portion of the shoreline around Sturgeon Bay in Door County. In all cases, the US Geological Survey's 1:24,000-scale digital raster graphics were used as the authority for the location of county boundary lines.

prcStep.stepDesc: In 2007, offset errors were discovered in the linework representing portions of Washington Island and Rock Island in Door County. The erroneous linework was replaced with the corresponding linework from the 1:24,000-scale Hydrography data. In the course of this work, other slight offsets were found and fixed; several of these were lines representing the boundary between Wisconsin and Michigan.

prcStep.stepDesc:
In November 2011, the Wisconsin legislature enacted Act 66, changing a portion of the boundary between Marquette County and Green Lake County. On December 5, 20011, Green Lake County GIS staff provided a shapefile delineating the new boundary. Using that shapefile as a reference, WI DNR/BTS staff edited the 24K WI County Boundary data layer to reflect the new boundary between Marquette and Green Lake County. In the process, very minor adjustments were also made to other portions of the Green Lake County boundary to agree with the shapefile provided by the county. WI DNR edits were completed on December 14, 2011.
Prior to these updates, the pre-existing, legacy versions of the SDEDNR.EN_COUNTY_BND_REGN_AR_24K feature class were assigned ArcGIS "low precision" data storage. The process of incorporating the new county boundary lines into the low precision SDEDNR.EN_COUNTY_BND_REGN_AR_24K feature class using a "high precision" source resulted in extremely small coordinate offsets throughout the feature class when comparing it with the previous version of SDEDNR.EN_COUNTY_BND_REGN_AR_24K. In comparing these offsets for sample areas around the state, the coordinate offsets were observed to be systematic offsets of approximately .2mm (two tenths of a millimeter) or less.
